</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,330,1370]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,279,330,356]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Male. 
<emphasis box="[363,426,330,355]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Head</emphasis>
: Face moderately produced, gradually sloped or angled forward from antenna to oral margin (
<figureCitation box="[251,324,368,394]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–12" captionStartId="5.[151,276,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[225,1350,199,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-44@5.[224,1358,179,1918]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7–12. Male heads, lateral. 7. Afroestricus flavipes (Loew); 8. Cophinopoda pulchripes (Bigot); 9. Longibeccus fuscovittatus (Ricardo); 10. Michotamia coarctata (Macquart); 11. Ommatius neotenellus Bromley; 12. Pygommatius litoreus (Scarbrough &amp; Marascia)." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
); bristles limited to lower 1/2 of face, only short setae dorsally. Flagellum (
<figureCitation box="[1221,1292,368,394]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="4.[150,270,1948,1972]" captionTargetBox="[396,1217,190,1930]" captionTargetId="figure-50@4.[384,1225,175,1944]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Male antennae. 1. Afroestricus flavipes (Loew); 2. Cophinopoda pulchripes (Bigot); 3. Longibeccus fuscovittatus (Ricardo); 4. Michotamia coarctata (Macquart); 5. Ommatius neotenellus Bromley; 6. Thallosia congoicola (Oldroyd). Abbr.: flgm=flagellum; ped=pedicel; sc=scape." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
) wider than and as long as scape+pedicel combined; surface sparsely punctuate. Proboscis equal to vertical height of compound eye, slightly compressed medially with vertical height greater than diameter; apex flattened dorsoventrally, awl-shape (
<figureCitation box="[469,542,480,506]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–12" captionStartId="5.[151,276,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[225,1350,199,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-44@5.[224,1358,179,1918]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7–12. Male heads, lateral. 7. Afroestricus flavipes (Loew); 8. Cophinopoda pulchripes (Bigot); 9. Longibeccus fuscovittatus (Ricardo); 10. Michotamia coarctata (Macquart); 11. Ommatius neotenellus Bromley; 12. Pygommatius litoreus (Scarbrough &amp; Marascia)." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
). Anterior scutal setae much shorter than scape. 
<emphasis box="[1117,1177,480,505]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Wing</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1194,1293,480,506]" captionStart="FIGURES 30–36" captionStartId="12.[150,271,1898,1922]" captionTargetBox="[154,1435,203,1857]" captionTargetId="figure-61@12.[150,1436,194,1877]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 30–36. Longibeccus fuscovittatus (Ricardo), male wing and terminalia. 30. Right wing; 31–33. Lateral, dorsal and ventral views; 34. Gonostylus; 35–36. Aedeagus, dorsal and lateral views. Abbr.: r4, m3=cells; cerc=cercus; epand=epandrium; epiph= epiphallus; goncx=gonocoxite; hypd=hypandrium; pvapod=posteroventral aedeagal apodeme." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs. 30</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1306,1339,480,506]" captionStart="FIGURES 41–47" captionStartId="18.[150,268,1749,1773]" captionTargetBox="[151,1431,198,1719]" captionTargetId="figure-196@18.[151,1436,197,1729]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 41–47. Longibeccus imperator (Oldroyd), male, wing and terminalia. 41. Left wing. Figures 42–44. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 45. Gonostylus; 46–47. Aedeagus, dorsal and lateral views. Abbr.: cerc=cercus; distph=disti phallus; epand=epandrium; ep iph=epiphallus; goncx=gon ocoxit e; hypd=hyp andrium; pvapod=posteroventral apodeme." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">41</figureCitation>
): Cell r 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1428,1436,496,510]" fontSize="6" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">1</subScript>
narrowly pointed; base of cell r 
<subScript attach="left" box="[525,533,536,550]" fontSize="6" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">4</subScript>
at or just before apex of cell d; R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[937,945,536,550]" fontSize="6" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">4</subScript>
slightly concave apically, joining C at or just below wing apex. 
<emphasis box="[428,473,561,586]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Leg</emphasis>
: Metathoracic femur with short, brown, spur-like, anteroventral bristles, about twice as long as ventral setae. 
<emphasis box="[527,659,598,623]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Terminalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[677,826,597,623]" captionStart="FIGURES 30–36" captionStartId="12.[150,271,1898,1922]" captionTargetBox="[154,1435,203,1857]" captionTargetId="figure-61@12.[150,1436,194,1877]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 30–36. Longibeccus fuscovittatus (Ricardo), male wing and terminalia. 30. Right wing; 31–33. Lateral, dorsal and ventral views; 34. Gonostylus; 35–36. Aedeagus, dorsal and lateral views. Abbr.: r4, m3=cells; cerc=cercus; epand=epandrium; epiph= epiphallus; goncx=gonocoxite; hypd=hypandrium; pvapod=posteroventral aedeagal apodeme." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs. 31–36</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[840,922,597,623]" captionStart="FIGURES 41–47" captionStartId="18.[150,268,1749,1773]" captionTargetBox="[151,1431,198,1719]" captionTargetId="figure-196@18.[151,1436,197,1729]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 41–47. Longibeccus imperator (Oldroyd), male, wing and terminalia. 41. Left wing. Figures 42–44. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 45. Gonostylus; 46–47. Aedeagus, dorsal and lateral views. Abbr.: cerc=cercus; distph=disti phallus; epand=epandrium; ep iph=epiphallus; goncx=gon ocoxit e; hypd=hyp andrium; pvapod=posteroventral apodeme." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">42–47</figureCitation>
): Epandrium deeply excised apically with contrasting shorter dorsal and longer ventral arms, former with several minute denticles along ventral margin. Aedeagal sheath inflated and produced dorsally, forming an epiphallus which extends above and beyond distiphallus in dorsal view. Female (
<figureCitation box="[576,718,709,735]" captionStart="FIGURES 37–40" captionStartId="13.[151,274,1477,1501]" captionTargetBox="[162,1433,207,1417]" captionTargetId="figure-234@13.[151,1436,194,1456]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 37–40. Longibeccus fuscovittatus (Ricardo), female terminalia. 37–38. Dorsal and ventral views; 39. Spermathecae; 40. Genital fork. Abbr.: cerc=cercus; tg8, tg9=tergite 8, tergite 9; st8=sternite 8." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs. 37–40</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[730,808,709,735]" captionStart="FIGURES 48–51" captionStartId="19.[151,276,1926,1950]" captionTargetBox="[159,1428,693,1895]" captionTargetId="figure-293@19.[151,1436,665,1905]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 48–51. Longibeccus imperator (Oldroyd), female terminalia. 48–49. Dorsal and ventral views; 50. Spermathecae; 51. Genital fork. Abbr.: cerc=cercus; tg8= tergite 8, tg9=tergite 9; st7=sternite 7, st8=sternite 8." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">48–51</figureCitation>
). Sparse, unusually stout, bristles on apical margin of abdominal segments 7. Cerci triangular, broad basally, fused medially, without membranous line between cerci; base of cercus extends ventrally, fusing with ventral lamella. Spermathecae oval, slightly longer than wide.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[198,591,858,885]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,330,1370]" box="[198,591,858,885]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,351,858,884]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Distribution</emphasis>
. Subsaharan Africa.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[198,1295,896,922]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,330,1370]" box="[198,1295,896,922]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,331,896,922]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Etymology</emphasis>
. Latin combination 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scarbrough" authorityYear="2010" box="[569,717,897,922]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Longibeccus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[569,717,897,922]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Longibeccus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Refers to the long proboscis. Gender masculine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,330,1370]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,312,933,959]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scarbrough" authorityYear="2010" box="[332,480,934,959]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Longibeccus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[332,480,934,959]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Longibeccus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is proposed to accommodate 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ricardo" authorityYear="1900" box="[858,1140,934,959]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscovittatus">
<emphasis box="[858,1140,934,959]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Ommatius fuscovittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Oldroyd" authorityYear="1936" box="[1208,1365,934,959]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Longibeccus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imperator">
<emphasis box="[1208,1365,934,959]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">O. imperator</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It is distinguished by the characters in the key and diagnosis, especially the gently sloped face, unusual shape of the flagellum, long proboscis, wing venation (
<figureCitation box="[686,767,1008,1034]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="4.[150,270,1948,1972]" captionTargetBox="[396,1217,190,1930]" captionTargetId="figure-50@4.[384,1225,175,1944]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Male antennae. 1. Afroestricus flavipes (Loew); 2. Cophinopoda pulchripes (Bigot); 3. Longibeccus fuscovittatus (Ricardo); 4. Michotamia coarctata (Macquart); 5. Ommatius neotenellus Bromley; 6. Thallosia congoicola (Oldroyd). Abbr.: flgm=flagellum; ped=pedicel; sc=scape." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs. 3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[780,797,1008,1034]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–12" captionStartId="5.[151,276,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[225,1350,199,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-44@5.[224,1358,179,1918]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7–12. Male heads, lateral. 7. Afroestricus flavipes (Loew); 8. Cophinopoda pulchripes (Bigot); 9. Longibeccus fuscovittatus (Ricardo); 10. Michotamia coarctata (Macquart); 11. Ommatius neotenellus Bromley; 12. Pygommatius litoreus (Scarbrough &amp; Marascia)." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">9</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[809,841,1008,1034]" captionStart="FIGURES 30–36" captionStartId="12.[150,271,1898,1922]" captionTargetBox="[154,1435,203,1857]" captionTargetId="figure-61@12.[150,1436,194,1877]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 30–36. Longibeccus fuscovittatus (Ricardo), male wing and terminalia. 30. Right wing; 31–33. Lateral, dorsal and ventral views; 34. Gonostylus; 35–36. Aedeagus, dorsal and lateral views. Abbr.: r4, m3=cells; cerc=cercus; epand=epandrium; epiph= epiphallus; goncx=gonocoxite; hypd=hypandrium; pvapod=posteroventral aedeagal apodeme." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">30</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[852,884,1008,1034]" captionStart="FIGURES 41–47" captionStartId="18.[150,268,1749,1773]" captionTargetBox="[151,1431,198,1719]" captionTargetId="figure-196@18.[151,1436,197,1729]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 41–47. Longibeccus imperator (Oldroyd), male, wing and terminalia. 41. Left wing. Figures 42–44. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 45. Gonostylus; 46–47. Aedeagus, dorsal and lateral views. Abbr.: cerc=cercus; distph=disti phallus; epand=epandrium; ep iph=epiphallus; goncx=gon ocoxit e; hypd=hyp andrium; pvapod=posteroventral apodeme." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">41</figureCitation>
), and the combined characters of the terminalia (
<figureCitation box="[159,303,1045,1071]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 30–36" captionStart-1="FIGURES 37–40" captionStartId-0="12.[150,271,1898,1922]" captionStartId-1="13.[151,274,1477,1501]" captionTargetBox-0="[154,1435,203,1857]" captionTargetBox-1="[162,1433,207,1417]" captionTargetId-0="figure-61@12.[150,1436,194,1877]" captionTargetId-1="figure-234@13.[151,1436,194,1456]" captionTargetPageId-0="12" captionTargetPageId-1="13" captionText-0="FIGURES 30–36. Longibeccus fuscovittatus (Ricardo), male wing and terminalia. 30. Right wing; 31–33. Lateral, dorsal and ventral views; 34. Gonostylus; 35–36. Aedeagus, dorsal and lateral views. Abbr.: r4, m3=cells; cerc=cercus; epand=epandrium; epiph= epiphallus; goncx=gonocoxite; hypd=hypandrium; pvapod=posteroventral aedeagal apodeme." captionText-1="FIGURES 37–40. Longibeccus fuscovittatus (Ricardo), female terminalia. 37–38. Dorsal and ventral views; 39. Spermathecae; 40. Genital fork. Abbr.: cerc=cercus; tg8, tg9=tergite 8, tergite 9; st8=sternite 8." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs. 31–40</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[316,394,1045,1071]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 41–47" captionStart-1="FIGURES 48–51" captionStartId-0="18.[150,268,1749,1773]" captionStartId-1="19.[151,276,1926,1950]" captionTargetBox-0="[151,1431,198,1719]" captionTargetBox-1="[159,1428,693,1895]" captionTargetId-0="figure-196@18.[151,1436,197,1729]" captionTargetId-1="figure-293@19.[151,1436,665,1905]" captionTargetPageId-0="18" captionTargetPageId-1="19" captionText-0="FIGURES 41–47. Longibeccus imperator (Oldroyd), male, wing and terminalia. 41. Left wing. Figures 42–44. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 45. Gonostylus; 46–47. Aedeagus, dorsal and lateral views. Abbr.: cerc=cercus; distph=disti phallus; epand=epandrium; ep iph=epiphallus; goncx=gon ocoxit e; hypd=hyp andrium; pvapod=posteroventral apodeme." captionText-1="FIGURES 48–51. Longibeccus imperator (Oldroyd), female terminalia. 48–49. Dorsal and ventral views; 50. Spermathecae; 51. Genital fork. Abbr.: cerc=cercus; tg8= tergite 8, tg9=tergite 9; st7=sternite 7, st8=sternite 8." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">42–51</figureCitation>
). The large plate-like epiphallus concealing the distiphallus dorsally is diagnostic of the genus (35, 36, 46, 47). The epiphallus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scarbrough" authorityYear="2005" box="[644,787,1083,1108]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Afroestricus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[644,787,1083,1108]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Afroestricus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[804,891,1083,1109]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–18" captionStartId="7.[151,270,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[163,1423,297,1889]" captionTargetId="figure-89@7.[151,1436,269,1897]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 13–18. Afroestricus flavipes (Loew), male terminalia (reillustrated after Scarbrough 2005). 13–15. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 16. Aedeagus, lateral view; 17a–c. Spermathecae, A. flavipes; 18. Type labels, A. flavipes. Abbr.: cerc=cercus; distph=distiphallus; epand=epandrium; epiph= epiphallus; goncx=gonocoxite; hypd=hypandrium; pvapod=posteroventral aedeagal apodeme." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1958" box="[915,1075,1083,1108]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Cophinopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[915,1075,1083,1108]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Cophinopoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1092,1180,1083,1109]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–23" captionStartId="9.[151,269,1653,1677]" captionTargetBox="[164,1424,205,1624]" captionTargetId="figure-139@9.[161,1426,194,1632]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 19–23. Cophinopoda pulchripes Bigot, male terminalia. 19. Epandrium; 20. Gonocoxite and hypandrium; 21. Aedeagus; 22. Female, sternite 8; 23. Spermathecae. Abbr.: distph=distiphallus; epiph=epiphallus; goncx=gonocoxite; pvapod=posteroventral aedeagal apodeme; spmth caps= spermathecal capsule." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schiner" authorityYear="1866" box="[1203,1371,1083,1108]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Emphysomera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1203,1371,1083,1108]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Emphysomera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 24–29" captionStartId="10.[151,271,1811,1835]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,389,1783]" captionTargetId="figure-129@10.[151,1436,381,1790]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 24–29. Emphysomera atrogaster Bigot (reillustrated after Scarbrough &amp; Marascia 1996). 24. Right wing. 25–26. Lateral and dorsal views, terminalia; 27. Aedeagus, lateral view; 28.Male abdomen; 29. Spermathecae. Abbr.; epand=epandrium, epiph=epiphallus, distph=distiphallus, hypd=hypandrium, goncxp=gonocoxital process, r =4th radial 4 cell; pvapod=posteroventral aedeagal apodeme." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Oldroyd" authorityYear="1970" box="[250,362,1121,1146]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Thallosia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[250,362,1121,1146]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Thallosia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[379,482,1120,1146]" captionStart="FIGURES 102–105" captionStartId="39.[151,270,1878,1902]" captionTargetBox="[155,1430,195,1827]" captionTargetId="figure-52@39.[150,1436,194,1857]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURES 102–105. Thallosia congiola Oldroyd (reillustrated from Tsacas &amp; Artigas 1994). 102. Epandrium, lateral; 103. Gonocoxite and hypandrium, lateral; 104. Aedeagus, lateral; 105. Female terminalia, ventral view. Abbr.: distph=distiphallus; epiph=epiphallus; goncx=gonocoxite; hypd=hypandrium; pvapod=posteroventral aedeagal apodeme; tg8=tergite 8." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 104</figureCitation>
) is also dorsal prominent but otherwise structurally different. The cercus which extends onto the ventral surface of the ventral lamella and the oval spermathecal bulbs are distinctive of females (
<figureCitation box="[262,363,1195,1221]" captionStart="FIGURES 37–40" captionStartId="13.[151,274,1477,1501]" captionTargetBox="[162,1433,207,1417]" captionTargetId="figure-234@13.[151,1436,194,1456]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 37–40. Longibeccus fuscovittatus (Ricardo), female terminalia. 37–38. Dorsal and ventral views; 39. Spermathecae; 40. Genital fork. Abbr.: cerc=cercus; tg8, tg9=tergite 8, tergite 9; st8=sternite 8." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs. 39</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[377,411,1195,1221]" captionStart="FIGURES 48–51" captionStartId="19.[151,276,1926,1950]" captionTargetBox="[159,1428,693,1895]" captionTargetId="figure-293@19.[151,1436,665,1905]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 48–51. Longibeccus imperator (Oldroyd), female terminalia. 48–49. Dorsal and ventral views; 50. Spermathecae; 51. Genital fork. Abbr.: cerc=cercus; tg8= tergite 8, tg9=tergite 9; st7=sternite 7, st8=sternite 8." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">50</figureCitation>
). In other genera, the cercus covers only the dorsal surface of the pygidium, and the spermathecal bulbs are usually 3 or more times longer than wide and recurved (
<figureCitation box="[1106,1206,1232,1258]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–18" captionStartId="7.[151,270,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[163,1423,297,1889]" captionTargetId="figure-89@7.[151,1436,269,1897]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 13–18. Afroestricus flavipes (Loew), male terminalia (reillustrated after Scarbrough 2005). 13–15. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 16. Aedeagus, lateral view; 17a–c. Spermathecae, A. flavipes; 18. Type labels, A. flavipes. Abbr.: cerc=cercus; distph=distiphallus; epand=epandrium; epiph= epiphallus; goncx=gonocoxite; hypd=hypandrium; pvapod=posteroventral aedeagal apodeme." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs. 17</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1220,1252,1232,1258]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–23" captionStartId="9.[151,269,1653,1677]" captionTargetBox="[164,1424,205,1624]" captionTargetId="figure-139@9.[161,1426,194,1632]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 19–23. Cophinopoda pulchripes Bigot, male terminalia. 19. Epandrium; 20. Gonocoxite and hypandrium; 21. Aedeagus; 22. Female, sternite 8; 23. Spermathecae. Abbr.: distph=distiphallus; epiph=epiphallus; goncx=gonocoxite; pvapod=posteroventral aedeagal apodeme; spmth caps= spermathecal capsule." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">23</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1265,1297,1232,1258]" captionStart="FIGURES 64–66" captionStartId="28.[150,269,1612,1636]" captionTargetBox="[190,1406,180,1598]" captionTargetId="figure-168@28.[183,1412,170,1608]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURES 64–66. Ommatius coperitus n. sp., female terminalia. 64. Ventral view; 65. Genital fork; 66. Spermathecae, posterior view. Abbr.: cerc=cercus; st8=sternite 8; vl=ventral lamella; spmth=spermatheca; spmth duct=spermatheca with coiled duct; spmth vlv=spermathecal valve." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">66</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1311,1343,1232,1258]" captionStart="FIGURES 79–82" captionStartId="31.[151,277,1974,1998]" captionTargetBox="[204,1392,446,1943]" captionTargetId="figure-132@31.[191,1402,433,1972]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURES 79–82. Ommatius neotenellus Bromley, female terminalia. 79–80. Dorsal and ventral views; 81. Spermathecae; 82. Genital fork." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">81</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1356,1390,1232,1258]" captionStart="FIGURES 95–98" captionStartId="36.[151,269,1976,2000]" captionTargetBox="[210,1392,448,1946]" captionTargetId="figure-142@36.[192,1407,430,1990]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURES 95–98. Ommatius ultimus n. sp., female terminalia. 95–96. Dorsal and ventral views; 97. Spermathecae; 98. Genital fork." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">97</figureCitation>
). In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Macquart" authorityYear="1839" box="[151,293,1270,1295]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Michotamia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,293,1270,1295]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Michotamia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the spermathecal duct is looped or tightly coiled (
<figureCitation box="[887,974,1270,1296]" captionStart="FIGURES 52–57" captionStartId="22.[151,274,1863,1887]" captionTargetBox="[190,1395,266,1833]" captionTargetId="figure-94@22.[186,1401,239,1871]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 52–57. Michotamia coarctata Macquart, female. 52. Right wing; 53. Sternite 8 with genital apodeme (sternite 10?); 54. Genital furca; 55. Spermatheca with coiled duct; 56. Michotamia aurata (Fabricius 1794) (Oriental species; Scarrough &amp; Hill 2000), male terminalia, lateral view; 57. Aedeagus, lateral view. Abbr.: genapod=genital apodeme; flgm=flagellum; spmth=spermatheca; spmth duct=spermatheca with coiled duct; spmth vlv=spermathecal valve; st8=sternite 8; tg8=tergite 8." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 55</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,330,1370]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scarbrough" authorityYear="2010" box="[197,346,1307,1332]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Longibeccus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[197,346,1307,1332]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Longibeccus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is confined to the African Continent with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ricardo" authorityYear="1900" box="[851,1032,1307,1332]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscovittatus">
<emphasis box="[851,1032,1307,1332]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">L. fuscovittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
widespread whereas 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Oldroyd" authorityYear="1936" box="[1286,1436,1307,1332]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Longibeccus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imperator">
<emphasis box="[1286,1436,1307,1332]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">L. imperator</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are only recorded from equatorial Africa (
<figureCitation box="[642,745,1344,1370]" captionStart="FIGURE 108" captionStartId="42.[151,255,1771,1795]" captionTargetBox="[157,1428,461,1746]" captionTargetId="figure-217@42.[150,1436,455,1750]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="FIGURE 108. Distribution of Longibeccus, new genus and Metommatus, new status in the Afrotropical Region." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 108</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
